    "11788893": {
      "title": "Desensitization of canonical transient receptor potential channel 5 by protein kinase C",
      "abstract": "The classic type of transient receptor potential channel (TRPC) is a molecular candidate for Ca2+-permeable cation channel in mammalian cells. TRPC5 is desensitized rapidly after activation by G protein-coupled receptor. Herein we report our investigation into the desensitization of mTRPC5 and localization of the molecular determinants of this desensitization using mutagenesis. TRPC5 was initially activated by muscarinic stimulation using 100 μM carbachol (CCh) and then decayed rapidly even in the presence of CCh (desensitization). Increased EGTA or omission of MgATP in the pipette solution slowed the rate of this desensitization. The protein kinase C (PKC) inhibitors, 1 μM chelerythrine, 100 nM GF109203X, or PKC peptide inhibitor (19–36), inhibited this desensitization of TRPC5 activated by 100 μM CCh. When TRPC5 current was activated by intracellular GTPγS, PKC inhibitors prevented TRPC5 desensitization and the mutation of TRPC5 T972 to alanine slowed the desensitization process dramatically. We conclud..."
